very. it washed away all the fields near the river. we lost everything that year.
we used to listen to stories from our grandmothers and play games like 'bagh-bakri'.
what is the reason behind singing 'baithki holi' songs?
who was sumitranandan pant? i have heard his name.
he was a very famous poet from our kumaon, born in kausani.
do you remember when the first bus reached our village?
how was this village school built? did the government make it?
no, our forefathers donated the land and built the first two rooms themselves.
apart from gilli-danda, what other games did you play as a child?
we used to play 'daandi-par', a game similar to kabaddi. it required a lot of strength.
is it true that the idol in the jageshwar temple appeared on its own?
that is the belief. it's a very ancient and powerful temple.
tell me the story of gangnath devta. why is he worshipped?
he was a prince who was betrayed and killed. now he is worshipped as a god of justice.
what was the 'hariyala' festival like in the old days?
it was a big celebration of farming. we used to make dolls of shiva-parvati and worship them.
i heard there was a great famine ('sukaal') long ago. was it true?
yes, my grandfather used to tell stories about it. there was no water or food for months.
how were weddings conducted in your time? were they so grand?
no, no. they were simple. the groom's party would come on foot, and the feast was simple dal and rice.
why do we apply 'pithya' (rice paste) on the forehead during puja?
it is considered auspicious and is a symbol of purity and blessings.
did any freedom fighter from our village participate in the struggle against the british?
yes, mohan singh from the lower village was a brave freedom fighter. he was even jailed for it.
what was people's reaction when the first radio came to the village?
they used to call it the 'box that sings'. people would gather from far away just to listen to it.
this bridge seems very old. when was it built?
i heard about a game called 'bagh-bakri'. how was it played?
it's a strategy game for two people, played with stones on a drawn board. it's like chess.
why is the patal bhuvaneshwar cave considered so sacred?
was there any famous queen in kumaon's history?
yes, jiya rani was a very brave queen. there are many folk tales about her courage.
what is the 'bhitauli' ritual? i have only heard the name.
in the month of chaitra, a brother would visit his married sister with gifts and sweets. it was a very important custom.
how did people cope when the hailstorm destroyed all the crops?
it was very difficult. people had to survive on stored grains and by selling their animals.
in old times, how did you grind wheat and corn?
we used to go to the water mill ('gharat'). it was a day's work.
what is the story behind celebrating the 'jaagar' for golu devta?
people invoke his spirit to seek justice for their problems. he is known as the god of justice.
who was gaura pant 'shivani'?
she was a very famous writer from kumaon. her stories beautifully depicted our culture.
when was the first post office opened in this area?
i think it was opened in the 1970s. before that, mail used to come by foot.
this primary school seems quite old. who funded its construction?
a rich trader from our village, who lived in the city, donated all the money for it.
was the thal mela as crowded in your childhood as it is today?
they say this old peepal tree is sacred. why so?
it is believed that a divine spirit resides in it. no one dares to cut its branches.
he is a protector spirit of the boundaries and forests, not a ghost. we worship him.
did people celebrate nauratri with a 'kalash sthapana' in the old days too?
yes, this tradition is very ancient. we also used to plant 'jau' (barley) in a pot.
how did the village survive the terrible landslide of 1998?
many houses were destroyed, but everyone helped each other rebuild their lives. the unity was strong.
grandma, what kind of clothes did you wear when you were a bride?
i wore a red 'pichhaura' and a silver 'nath'. there were no lehengas back then.
why is it a tradition to prepare 'bade' (urad dal fritters) during festivals?
they are considered auspicious and are first offered to the gods before we eat them.
who was anasuya prasad bahuguna? i saw a statue of him in the city.
he was a great leader from garhwal who fought against british rule and social evils.
i heard people used to communicate using drum beats. is that true?
this suspension bridge seems to be from the british era.
you are right. it was built by them to cross the river. it's over a hundred years old.
tell me about the wrestling competitions ('dangal') that used to happen at the fair.
wrestlers used to come from far and wide. the winner was given a turban and a lot of respect.
what is the story of this 'haat kalika' temple?
it is said that adi shankaracharya himself established the idol of the goddess here.
it is just a legend. scientists say it is some kind of gas.
why is the 'olgia' or 'ghee sankranti' festival not so common now?
it was a harvest festival. as farming declined, so did the festival.
i heard a cholera epidemic spread in the village a long time ago.
yes, many people died because there were no doctors or hospitals nearby.
what was the staple food of our ancestors? was it rice?
no, it was mostly millet ('madua') and barley ('jau'). rice was cooked only on special occasions.
why is it a tradition to make 'aipan' art at the entrance of the house?
it is done to welcome the gods and to bring good fortune to the home.
tell me about chandra singh garhwali. was he from our region?
he was from garhwal, but he is a hero for all of uttarakhand. he refused to fire on unarmed freedom fighters.
when did people in the village start building concrete houses?
it started in the late 80s when people started earning money in the cities.
who laid the foundation stone of this ramleela ground?
yes, but the real chholiya dance used to be much more energetic and skilled.
why is the binsar mahadev temple surrounded by a dense forest?
it is a protected area. it's believed that lord shiva meditated here, so the forest is sacred.
is any nrega work starting in the village?
yes, they will be digging the canal from next week. you can get your name listed.
i heard your son has gone to delhi to find a job.
yes, there is no work here. he will try to find work in some company.
the wheat crop is turning yellow. what should we do?
it needs urea fertilizer. we will have to bring it from the market.
sister, will you come with me tomorrow to cut grass for the cows?
my plough is broken. can i borrow yours for a day?
yes, take it. but its blade is a bit blunt. you'll have to sharpen it.
did you hear? mohan's son got a job in the army.
that's wonderful news! his family's hardships will now end.
are you going to the forest to collect firewood tomorrow?
yes, the firewood at home is finished. let's go together.
we need to take the potatoes to the haldwani market. how will we go?
let's hire a jeep together. the cost will be divided.
how much milk is your buffalo giving these days?
about three liters a day. i sell two liters to the dairy.
look at the new jacket your son brought from delhi. it's very nice.
yes, he brought clothes for everyone in the family.
what is the daily wage for the road construction work?
they are giving 400 rupees, but the work is very hard.
my son is not happy in the city. he wants to come back.
city life is not for everyone. what work will he do here?
you are right. all our hard work will go in vain.
i need help bringing the fodder down from the hill.
okay, i will come in the evening. we will bring it together.
the handle of my sickle is broken. can the carpenter fix it?
yes, he will fit a new handle. it will cost about fifty rupees.
i heard ramu sent a lot of money from dubai.
yes, they are building a new concrete house now.
we need to collect dried pine needles ('pirul') for the cowshed.
let's go tomorrow. the forest floor is covered with it.
what price are they offering for tomatoes in the market?
the price has dropped a lot. it's only ten rupees a kilo.
my cow seems sick. she is not eating the feed.
you should call the vet. it might affect her milk.
your daughter came back from the city. did she bring a gift for you?
yes, she brought a very beautiful saree for me.
the nrega payment hasn't come for three months.
yes, everyone is troubled. we should go and ask the pradhan.
delhi has more opportunities, but the expenses are also very high there.
we need to repair the walls of the terrace fields before the rains.
yes, otherwise all the soil will be washed away.
the grass in the upper forest is very long and good.
but it's risky to go there alone. a leopard is often seen there.
go to the carpenter in the market. he keeps good quality wooden handles.
bishan singh's pension from the army has started.
that's good. now he can live his life comfortably.
the forest guard is not allowing us to collect firewood.
should we sell the ginger now or wait for the price to increase?
wait for a month. the price will definitely go up after the rains.
i want to sell my goat. do you know any buyer?
the butcher from the town comes on sundays. you can talk to him.
you bought new shoes from the city? they look very expensive.
no, they are not expensive. there's a big sale in the city these days.
is there any other work available besides nrega?
sometimes there is work at the new resort being built, but it's not regular.
life in delhi is very difficult. it's hard to save any money.
that is true. but what to do? there is no livelihood here.
yes, the timely rains were very beneficial.
there is no grass left in the nearby forest.
we will have to go to the far forest now. it's a whole day's work.
yes, he sits there every tuesday. you will find him there.
is it true that soldiers get a lot of facilities?
yes, their children get a good education and they get a pension after retirement.
be careful while going to the forest. the forest ranger is on patrol.
okay, thank you for the warning. i will only collect dry wood.
i need to sell the turmeric. is the market rate good?
yes, the rate is good right now. you should sell it.
the cooperative dairy is closed today?
yes, it's sunday. they have a holiday on sunday.
your son has become very stylish after living in the city.
yes, but he still respects the village traditions. that's what matters.
we worked for 15 days in nrega, but the money has not been credited.
the money comes from the government. it always takes time.
ramu has come back from haldwani. he didn't get any job.
it's very difficult to find a job without any skills.
this time, insects have infested the bean crop.
we need to spray some insecticide. otherwise, the whole crop will be ruined.
my hands are hurting from cutting so much grass.
yes, it's a very laborious job. but we have to do it for the animals.
can you lend me your spade? i need to dig a small pit.
sure, take it. it is lying near the cowshed.
he seems very proud after getting a government job.
let him be. pride doesn't last long.
is it allowed to take wood from the community forest ('van panchayat')?
yes, but only for personal use and you have to take permission first.
what is the going rate for cucumbers in the city market?
you will get it at the veterinary hospital in the main market.
did he bring any sweets from the city?
yes, he brought a box of 'bal mithai'. it was very tasty.
the gram panchayat adhikari will come tomorrow to list the names.
my brother has found a job in a hotel in mussoorie.
that's very good. the salary in hotels is good during the tourist season.
yes, let's prepare the fields tomorrow.
today, i have to go far to fetch fodder. can you look after my child?
yes, don't worry. leave him here with me.
i need to borrow a spade and a pickaxe for a day.
take them, but please return them by the evening.
money changes people. we should stay away from such people.
no, it is strictly forbidden. there is a heavy fine for it.
the middlemen in the market are giving a very low price for our produce.
that's why we should try to sell it directly to the customers.
the quality of the cattle feed from the government store is very bad.
you are right. it's better to buy from a private shop, even if it's expensive.
the jeans your son brought look very modern.
yes, this is the fashion in the cities these days.
grandfather, do you remember the old path that went through the forest to the temple?
oh yes. it was a narrow, winding path. we were always scared of wild animals on that route.
did you really listen to cricket commentary on the radio all day?
yes! the whole village would gather at the pradhan's house. it was more exciting than watching tv today.
is it true you used to steal mangoes from the landlord's orchard as a child?
it could take anywhere from 15 days to a month. we used to wait eagerly for the postman.
did people really sleep on the open terrace during summer nights?
absolutely. under the starry sky. we would listen to stories from our grandmother until we fell asleep.
what was your reaction when you first saw a train?
i thought it was a giant iron snake! i was so scared i hid behind my father.
do you remember the big peepal tree that used to be at the village entrance?
yes, all village meetings used to happen under that tree. it was like our assembly hall.
which radio program was your favorite?
i never missed 'binaca geetmala' on wednesdays. ameen sayani's voice was magical.
did you ever get a scolding for playing pranks on the village elders?
was it difficult to write letters? did everyone know how to write?
no, very few people were literate. we used to go to the schoolmaster to get our letters written.
yes, the water was so pure and sweet back then. we didn't need any filters.
when did you first taste ice cream?
when i went to nainital for the first time as a child. i thought it was some kind of sweet, cold butter!
what was the village like before this main road was built?
did you ever send a song request on the radio?
yes, through a postcard. and when they announced my name and played the song, i felt like a celebrity!
what was the most common mischief you did in your childhood?
ringing someone's doorbell and running away. it was simple but so much fun.
how did you feel when you received a letter from family while working in the city?
it felt like they had come to meet me in person. i used to read it over and over again.
is it true that wedding processions used to travel for two or three days?
yes, if the bride's village was far away. they used to rest in villages along the way.
how did it feel to see a movie in a cinema hall for the first time?
do you miss the old mud houses with thatched roofs?
yes, they were cool in summers and warm in winters. these concrete houses feel like ovens.
was the radio the only source of news back then?
yes, we used to wait for the 8 o'clock news to know what was happening in the country and the world.
tell me a story of your mischief at school.
once we let a calf loose in the headmaster's office. we got suspended for a week!
did you ever receive a money order?
yes, my brother used to send his salary by money order from the army. the postman was a very important person for us.
i heard people used to gather for a community bonfire ('ghuri') every night in winter.
yes, it was a time for gossip, storytelling, and singing. those nights were beautiful.
what was the first vehicle you ever sat in?
it was an old, rattling bus to haldwani. i felt sick the whole way, but it was an adventure.
i feel the taste of vegetables grown in our own fields was different back then.
it was, because we didn't use any chemical fertilizers. everything was organic and pure.
yes, a program called 'krishi jagat' used to air in the evening. it was very informative.
did you ever get punished for not doing your homework?
our master ji used to make us stand on the bench with our hands up. it was very embarrassing.
how did you send urgent news before phones existed?
we had to send someone running to the next village or send a message via telegram from the city.
is it true that there were no fans in houses, even in summer?
yes, there were no fans. but the mud houses were naturally cool, and we had the fresh mountain breeze.
when you first visited a big city like delhi, what amazed you the most?
the tall buildings and the endless stream of cars! i had never seen anything like it.
do you remember the community water mill ('gharat')?
of course. it was a meeting spot for all the women. we used to sing songs while waiting for our turn.
was listening to the radio a family activity?
yes, after dinner, the whole family would sit together and listen. there was only one radio in the house.
what happened when you were caught stealing sugarcane from the fields?
the farmer made us eat the entire bundle right there! i felt sick for two days.
were letters the only way to stay in touch with relatives living far away?
yes, that was the only way. a letter was a precious thing in those days.
did you really use stone grinders ('chakki') to make flour at home?
yes, every morning. it was hard work but the rotis made from that flour were very tasty.
what was the first 'mithai' (sweet) you ever tasted from a shop?
it was a 'jalebi'. i still remember its taste. it felt like nectar.
i miss the sound of the cowbells in the evening when the cattle returned home.
me too. that sound meant the day's work was over and it was time to rest.
did the radio battery last long?
remember how we used to swim in the river, against our parents' warnings?
yes, and we would come home and lie that we fell in the stream by mistake.
was the postman a respected figure in the village?
very much so. he brought news from our loved ones. everyone used to offer him tea and water.
how did you manage without refrigerators in the past?
we used to keep milk and yogurt in earthen pots to keep them cool. nature was our refrigerator.
how did you feel when you held a camera for the first time?
i was afraid i would break it! it seemed like a very complex and magical device.
life seemed simpler then, didn't it?
it was harder, but simpler. people had less, but they were more content.
i remember the crackling sound of the radio when the signal was weak.
yes, we had to constantly adjust the antenna to catch the station.
did you ever bunk school to go to the village fair?
haha, once. but my father saw me there and the consequences were not pleasant.
what was written in the inland letters? were they just for news?
news, well-wishes, requests for money... a person's entire world was in that small blue paper.
did you use lanterns for light at night?
yes, lanterns and small earthen lamps ('diya'). the whole village would go dark by 9 pm.
when you first saw people wearing jeans, what did you think?
i thought they were very strange clothes. it looked so tight and uncomfortable!
did you go to the forest for firewood today?
a big pine tree has fallen and blocked the main path.
oh, really? now we'll have to take the longer route around the fields.
the monkeys from the jungle have ruined all the cucumbers.
ours too. they don't leave anything to eat.
i heard the forest guard caught hari with illegal wood.
yes, he was fined five thousand rupees.
the path to the spring is very overgrown with bushes.
true, it needs to be cleared soon.
let's go together tomorrow to collect fodder.
okay, what time should we leave?
i am going to collect some dry twigs for kindling.
did you find any mushrooms in the forest?
no, it hasn't rained enough yet. maybe next week.
some government people were surveying the forest.
yes, i saw them. they were marking the trees.
someone is cutting oak trees without permission.
this is very wrong. the whole forest will be destroyed like this.
a wild boar dug up my potato field last night.
these boars have become a huge menace.
are these wild berries edible?
yes, they are called kafal. they are very sweet when ripe.
i saw leopard pugmarks near the river this morning.
be careful then. don't go out alone after dark.
the firewood is still damp from yesterday's rain.
keep it in the sun for a while, it will dry out.
why is the forest department fencing off that area?
they are planting new saplings there, so they are protecting them.
the shortcut through the woods is impassable.
yes, it is full of thorny bushes.
my firewood stack is almost finished.
mine too. we'll have to go to the forest this week.
are the cuckoos singing already?
did you get the permit to collect fodder from the community forest?
not yet, the pradhan will distribute them tomorrow.
let's go look for some 'lingadu' (fiddlehead ferns) by the stream.
good idea! its vegetable is very tasty.
the wind last night broke a big branch off our walnut tree.
at least you will get some good firewood from it.
i hear someone is illegally selling pine resin.
they will get caught one day. these things don't stay hidden.
i need to wake up early to go collect fallen sticks.
yes, it's better to go before the sun gets too strong.
the forest floor is covered in pine needles.
we should collect them for the cowshed bedding.
is it true that the old path through the dense forest is haunted?
i almost slipped on the mossy stones in the forest.
be very careful, especially after the rain.
why were the forest officials taking photos?
they were documenting the damage from the recent forest fire.
the barking deer are getting very bold, they come right up to the village.
yes, i saw one near the school yesterday.
did you see that beautiful bird with a long tail?
yes, it's called a magpie. they are common in these woods.
someone has stripped the bark from the pine trees again.
they use it to sell for roofing. it kills the tree.
we need to clear the stinging nettles from the path.
let's do it this sunday. it's becoming a real problem.
yes, let's go. we'll find good, dry oak wood there.
the forest smells so good after the rain.
yes, the smell of wet earth and pine is wonderful.
the forest department has banned entry into the core zone.
why? is it because of the leopard sightings?
have the 'kilmora' berries ripened?
yes, some of them are black now. they are good for an upset stomach.
a whole troop of langurs is sitting on the oak trees.
they are probably eating the fresh leaves.
the village council has decided to fine anyone caught cutting green trees.
that is a very good decision. it was much needed.
i gathered a lot of pine cones today.
they are excellent for starting a fire in the winter.
the path down to the stream is very slippery.
yes, be careful. the moss on the rocks is dangerous.
is oak wood better than pine for burning?
yes, oak burns slowly and gives more heat.
did the forest fire reach near our village?
who's making that tapping sound in the forest?
it must be a woodpecker. they are always pecking at dead trees.
they are building a new forest rest house on the hill.
i saw that. it will bring more tourists here.
my grandfather knows a lot about medicinal plants from the forest.
the old generation has so much knowledge about these things.
the path is blocked by a landslide from the upper forest.
we will have to clear it ourselves. no one else will come.
the birds are eating all the ripe peaches.
yes, especially the parrots. they come in flocks.
be careful, the soil is very hard there.
did you see how many new stumps are in the forest?
yes, illegal felling is increasing day by day.
the forest department is organizing a tree planting drive next week.
that's a great initiative. we should all participate.
let's all go together to clear the village path on sunday.
yes, many hands make light work.
oh yes, they are everywhere once it starts raining.
i saw a porcupine on the way back from the forest.
they are shy creatures, you were lucky to see one.
why is the forest so silent today? no birds singing.
maybe it's going to rain heavily. animals can sense it.
they are auctioning the fallen trees from the forest.
the village should try to buy some for community use.
i am looking for 'bichhu ghas' (stinging nettle) to make a dish.
you'll find plenty near the damp areas by the stream.
the forest guard was asking who built a new shed near the forest boundary.
it's not allowed to build anything so close to the reserve forest.
my axe handle is broken. i need to make a new one.
use wood from the 'khair' tree, it's very strong.
i can hear a stream flowing somewhere deep inside the forest.
did you see the smoke rising from the forest?
yes, i hope it's not another forest fire.
we need to collect more grass for the cattle before winter.
yes, the stock is running low.
it means the monsoon is here to stay for a while.
the forest department fined some tourists for lighting a campfire.
it's very risky. a small spark can burn the whole forest.
my cow wandered off into the forest.
let's go look for her before it gets dark.
the rhododendron flowers are blooming beautifully.
yes, we should make some juice from them.
the government is giving subsidies for planting fruit trees.
that's good. it will help both the people and the forest.
the timber smugglers are getting more active these days.
the villagers should form a watch group to patrol at night.
i found a piece of 'guggul' resin in the forest.
it's very good for burning as incense during prayers.
the new forest ranger seems very strict.
it's good. maybe now the illegal activities will stop.
my sickle is blunt. i can't cut the grass.
you should sharpen it on the stone near the temple.
are there bears in this forest?
yes, in the upper regions. but they rarely come down.
let's do it this afternoon when the sun is not so harsh.
the forest department check post is stopping everyone.
they are checking for illegal timber being transported.
look at the fireflies! the forest looks magical.
it's one of the most beautiful sights in the summer evenings.
yes, i got a big bundle of 'maalu' leaves.
i'm worried the spring in the forest will dry up this summer.
it might. the water level is already very low.
it's as if the whole jungle has taken a bath.
a tree fell on prem's cowshed during the storm.
oh no! were the animals hurt?
someone has set traps for wild animals in the forest.
this is illegal and very cruel. we must inform the forest guard.
yes, at night, when everything is quiet, the sound travels far.
that's good to see. our hard work is paying off.
the monkeys are now snatching food from people's hands.
they have become fearless. we need to do something.
okay, its chutney is very delicious.
is there a forest committee in our village?
yes, but it's not very active these days.
the ropes made from 'bhabhar' grass are very strong.
yes, we use them for tying the firewood bundles.
the old forest temple has a very peaceful atmosphere.
true. i go there sometimes just to sit quietly.
they say a big snake lives in the hollow of that old tree.
could be true. it's best not to go near it.
the wind is making a strange whistling sound in the pine trees.
it sounds a bit spooky at night.
did you take the cattle for grazing today?
yes, i took them to the new pasture across the stream.
the honey from there is very pure, but it's very dangerous to get.
the school children went for a nature walk in the forest today.
my feet are sore from walking so much in the forest.
wash them with warm salt water. you will feel better.
is the rumor true that they found some old coins in the forest?
the mist is coming down from the forest. it's going to get cold.
yes, light the fire inside the house.
someone has lit a fire in the forest to clear land for farming.
the forest guard will be very angry if he finds out.
i'm making a broom with the wild grass from the forest.
they last much longer than the ones from the market.
the forest path is filled with dry, slippery pine needles.
yes, it's very difficult to walk on the slopes.
the partridges are calling. it's a very pleasant sound.
yes, especially in the mornings and evenings.
i need to repair the fence to keep the wild boars out.
use thorny branches. they are very effective.
do you remember when we used to play in that part of the forest as kids?
i have to go deep into the forest to get good soil for my plants.
the soil under the oak trees is the best, very fertile.
my goat ate some poisonous plant in the forest and got sick.
i saw some city people having a picnic and leaving all their trash behind.
that is so irresponsible. they are spoiling our forests.
i collected some 'timur' to keep with the grains.
yes, it keeps the insects away.
the forest department has built a water hole for the animals.
that's good. they won't have to come to the village for water in the summer.
the oak trees are shedding their leaves now.
this dry leaf litter is good for making manure.
did you hear that owl hooting all night?
yes, it was sitting on the big tree just behind my house.
a branch fell on the roof and broke some tiles.
we should cut the overhanging branches before the next storm.
the soil erosion from the deforested hill is getting worse.
yes, we need to plant more trees to hold the soil.
let's sit here in the shade of this tree for a while.
good idea, i'm tired of walking in the sun.
i got scared by a squirrel that suddenly ran past my feet.
they are so quick! you barely see them before they are gone.
the forest is our real wealth, we must protect it.
you are absolutely right. our life depends on it.
i am looking for 'buransh' flowers to offer at the temple.
you will find them on the trees on the upper slope.
is it okay to take fallen wood from the reserve forest?
only small twigs for domestic use. taking big logs is not allowed.
i tied a swing on the big banyan tree for the children.
that's lovely. they will have a lot of fun.
let's go and collect some. we can make chutney.
the forest guard put up a new sign about not littering.
i hope people will read it and follow the rule.
i think i have a thorn in my foot from the forest path.
let me see. we need to take it out carefully.
the government is promoting beekeeping in the villages.
it's a good source of income and helps pollinate the crops.
this part of the forest is so dense, the sunlight barely reaches the ground.
yes, it stays cool here even in the summer.
the echo in this valley is amazing.
we need to go and fetch our buffalo from the forest.
okay, let's go. it will be dark soon.
the forest department is cutting down the old, dangerous trees near the road.
it's a good thing. they could fall during a storm.
me too. it is very refreshing.
i'm going to soak some 'gahat' dal that i brought from the village fields.
oh, its soup is very delicious and warming in the winter.
true. we must respect them to live in harmony.
the children are collecting acorns from the forest floor.
a truck carrying logs overturned on the forest road.
was anyone hurt? the road is very narrow there.
we should go to the forest today, the weather is perfect.
yes, it's not too hot and not raining.
that part of the forest is a sacred grove.
yes, no one is allowed to cut any trees or plants there.
i saw a mongoose dart across the path.
they are good to have around, they keep snakes away.
the forest department is encouraging people to report illegal felling.
they have even announced a reward for informers.
look at the patterns the lichen makes on the tree bark.
it's so intricate and beautiful.
do these mushrooms grow back in the same spot every year?
yes, if the conditions are right. we must not damage the soil there.
it is. i could listen to it for hours.
we need to go and bring back the log we left in the forest.
let's take the bullocks to drag it.
the forest ranger is a good man, he always helps the villagers.
yes, he understands our needs and problems.
i'm making a walking stick from a sturdy branch i found.
it will be very useful on the steep paths.
the wild jasmine is in bloom, the whole forest is fragrant.
yes, the fragrance is especially strong in the evenings.
it's an old tradition to thank the forest for its bounty.
i saw a pine marten climbing a tree.
they are very agile. it's rare to spot them during the day.
the forest department has created fire lines to stop fires from spreading.
that's a smart move. i hope it works.
we need to stack the firewood properly so it stays dry.
the forest provides us with so much, from wood to water.
it is our duty to take care of it in return.
i'm going to collect clay from the forest for plastering the walls.
the red clay near the stream is very good for that.
a flock of wild pigeons just flew overhead.
they are probably going towards the fields to feed.
be careful while chopping wood, the axe is very sharp.
don't worry, i have been doing this since i was a child.
the forest guard warned us not to venture out at night because of the leopard.
it's better to be safe. we should listen to him.
can you identify this plant? i found it in the forest.
this is 'dolu'. its root is used in many traditional medicines.
it's so peaceful, it helps you fall asleep.
is it true they are making a road through the forest?
yes, many trees will be cut. it's sad.
the air feels so clean here, away from the city smoke.
that's the gift of our forests.
we should teach our children about the importance of the forest.
absolutely. they are the future guardians of this land.
the forest provides fodder for our animals all year round.
i'm looking for a special kind of smooth stone from the river for grinding spices.
you'll find many good ones in the deeper parts of the stream.
the government has put a ban on grazing in the newly planted area.
it's necessary to let the young saplings grow without disturbance.
i heard a strange animal call from the forest last night.
i need to go collect some pine sap for sealing the water pot.
be careful, it's very sticky.
the forest has given us life, and we are destroying it.
it's a sad truth. we need to wake up before it's too late.
my radio isn't working. it just makes a humming sound.
i have a bad cough. do you know any home remedy?
mix some honey with black pepper powder and lick it slowly. it gives great relief.
these ants are not going away. what should i do?
draw a line with turmeric powder where they come from. they won't cross it.
i'm using wood ash to clean the utensils today.
yes, it makes them shine like new. it's better than soap powder.
how do you keep the monkeys away from the cornfields?
my son is asking for a toy. what can i make quickly?
take a small bamboo stick and make a few holes in it. a small flute will be ready.
the roof is leaking right above the bed. the rain has started again.
for now, put a large plastic sheet on the roof and place heavy stones on its corners.
i heard you are washing your sweaters with 'reetha' (soapnuts).
yes, it cleans them well and doesn't spoil the wool. it's completely natural.
i'm thinking of growing broccoli in a small patch this time.
that's a good experiment. let's see how it grows in our soil and climate.
i have a terrible headache. the sun was very strong today.
grind some sandalwood and apply the paste on your forehead. you will get relief.
how do you preserve seeds for the next sowing season?
we mix them with wood ash and store them in a dry place. insects don't infest them.
a rat has entered the house and is causing a lot of trouble.
make a dough of flour and jaggery and place it inside a tin box trap.
the fan's speed is not changing. it's stuck on slow.
open the regulator and clean the dust from the contact points with an old toothbrush. it might work.
quickly apply some turmeric powder on it. it will stop the bleeding and prevent infection.
the floor of the courtyard has become very dusty.
let's plaster it with cow dung and clay tomorrow. it will be clean and solid.
i am making a scarecrow for the field.
good. put a black pot on its head, birds are more scared of that.
